Domestic Beers and Breweries

Mai Loan Tran/Zackary Gill

October 10, 2018

Introduction

We have been asked to help Budweiser identify which cities should host events for breweries.
The provided datasets contain two lists of 2410 US craft beers across 558 US breweries consisting of the style of beer, ABV (Alcohol by Volume), IBU (International Bitterness Units), and the brewery’s city and state.
Our exploration of the data identified the top 5 states with the most number of breweries to host events towards expansion of those existing markets. Alternatively, we identified 5 states with only one brewery each that could serve as opportunities into new markets. Another view of the data also suggests that events could be hosted in the 5 states with the most bitter beers to introduce beers that are less bitter.

Question 7

Chart 9 reflects an apparent positive relationship between IBU and ABV values.
The black dotted line is the mean ABV at that value of IBU. The yellow shading is the standard deviation. While there is positive correlation between the ABV and IBU with a maximum ABV value peaking out around 10%, there are two outliers that warrant further examination for inclusion or exclusion depending on additional questions of interest.

Chart 9: Alcohol By Volume vs International Bitterness Units of beer

Conclusion

Of the 2410 beers in the provided dataset, we propose events to be hosted in the top 5 states with the most number of breweries, Colorado (47), California (39), Michigan (32), Oregon (29), Texas (28). As shown in Chart 1, this presents opportunties to expand services in those existing markets whereas Washington DC, South Dakota, North Dakota, and West Virgina with one brewery per state are locations with opportunities to grow those markets. For introduction of less bitter beers where the median IBU is above 51, we propose events be hosted in Maine (61), West Virginia (57.5), Florida (55), Georgia (55), and Delaware (52) as shown in Chart 5.
